The codex-review blocker made concrete: the token is minted at acquisition, before any other side effect, and every later side effect re-reads the lock and proceeds only if it still holds its own token.

**Produces (src/learn/lock.rs):**
```rust
pub struct LockGuard { path: PathBuf, pub token: String }
pub enum Acquire { Held(LockGuard), Reclaimed(LockGuard), Busy }
pub fn acquire_at(dir: &Path, deadline: Duration, now_unix: i64) -> io::Result<Acquire>;
impl LockGuard {
    pub fn still_held(&self) -> bool;   // re-read learn/lock.json; parse; token == self.token
    pub fn release(self);               // remove file only if still_held
}
```
Lock file `learn/lock.json` = `{pid, started_at, token}` created with `OpenOptions::new().write(true).create_new(true)` (O_EXCL). On EEXIST: read the holder; STALE iff pid is dead (`libc::kill(pid, 0)` == -1 with ESRCH, `#[cfg(unix)]`) OR `now - started_at > 2 * deadline`; stale → remove + retry create_new once → `Reclaimed` (the CALLER counts a reclaim as one failure per Decision #3); live → `Busy`. Token = `state::random_hex(16)`.

**Steps:** (1) failing tests: fresh acquire Held; second acquire while held (live pid = our own) Busy; stale-by-age file gets Reclaimed; after an external process overwrites the lock file with a different token, `still_held()` is false and `release()` leaves the foreign lock intact. (2) Implement. (3) Green. (4) Commit `feat(learn): fencing-token lock with dead-pid/age stale reclaim`.

